{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658697"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:53:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:53:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20810"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20810","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20810"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0,0.22,0.7,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13685"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96158"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13685"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20810"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78886"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11578"},{"type":"tags","id":"11579"},{"type":"tags","id":"12643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32958"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32959"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96158","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96158"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism by which the CRISPR-Cas9 system targets specific DNA sequences?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["DNA methylation patterns guide Cas9 to specific sequences","Homologous recombination directs Cas9 to target sites","Cas9 protein recognises specific DNA sequences autonomously","Guide RNAs complementary to target DNA direct Cas9 nuclease","Cas9 binds to palindromic repeats throughout the genome"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CRISPR-Cas9 system targets specific DNA sequences through \u003Cstrong\u003Eguide RNAs complementary to target DNA direct Cas9 nuclease\u003C/strong\u003E. These guide RNAs (gRNAs) are approximately 20 bases in length and bind to the Cas9 protein. The gRNA-Cas9 complex then locates and binds to the complementary DNA sequence in the genome, allowing Cas9 to create double-stranded breaks at that precise location.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDNA methylation patterns guide Cas9 to specific sequences\u003C/strong\u003E - Cas9 targeting is not directed by DNA methylation patterns but by the complementary binding of guide RNAs to target DNA.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHomologous recombination directs Cas9 to target sites\u003C/strong\u003E - Homologous recombination is a repair mechanism that can be utilised after Cas9 creates double-stranded breaks, but it does not direct Cas9 to its target sites.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECas9 protein recognises specific DNA sequences autonomously\u003C/strong\u003E - Cas9 cannot target specific DNA sequences without guide RNAs; it requires the gRNA for sequence specificity.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECas9 binds to palindromic repeats throughout the genome\u003C/strong\u003E - While the CRISPR system in bacteria involves palindromic repeats, the engineered CRISPR-Cas9 system for gene editing does not target palindromic repeats but rather uses guide RNAs to target any desired sequence.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter Cas9 creates double-stranded breaks at the target site, the cell can repair these breaks through either non-homologous end joining (which often results in random mutations) or homologous recombination (which can introduce precise genetic modifications when a repair template is provided).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["CRISPR-Cas9 is a gene editing system derived from bacterial defence mechanisms against phages and plasmids.","The CRISPR-Cas9 system uses guide RNAs that are complementary to target DNA sequences to direct the Cas9 nuclease to specific genomic sites.","Gene editing with CRISPR-Cas9 can result in either random disruptive mutations through non-homologous end joining or precise genetic modifications through homologous recombination."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 1, The Cell as a Unit of Health and Disease; p. 6"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78886"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20810"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78886"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-31T13:23:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-31T13:23:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13685"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96158"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11578"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"The cell as a unit of health and disease","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":0,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:05:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:05:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}